The paper deals with distributed algorithms, specifically for the problem of computing a maximal independent set (MIS) in graphs. This falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) and also under Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also uses probabilistic techniques and tail inequalities, which are commonly used in Information Theory (cs.IT) and Numerical Analysis (cs.NA). Finally, the paper deals with analyzing the arboricity of graphs, which is a topic in Structural Complexity (cs.SI).
